erature and Art in an age of Religious Crisis</i> (Princeton UP, 1999); Margaret Aston, "Books 10-12: The Illustrations" <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.hrionline.ac.uk/johnfoxe/apparatus/introessays/astonbooks10-12theillustrationsessay.html">TAMO (The Acts and Monuments Online)</a>: offers unabridged text of the first four editions of <i>Acts and Monuments</i>, with search capacity and Introductory Essays. Cited here onward as TAMO.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Devorah Greenberg, "Reflexive Foxe: <i>The Book of Martyrs</i> Transformed, sixteenth to twenty-first centuries (unpublished dissertation, SFU, 2002) Chronological Bibliography, 294-5; William Haller, 118, 128-129; Warren Wooden, 11-13 among others.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">William Haller, <i>The Elect Nation: The Meaning and Relevance of Foxe\'s Book of Martyrs"</i> (New York, 1963) p. 58. That it was Grindal\'s project to produce an English \'book of martyrs\' see Patrick Collinson, <i>Archbishop Grindal The Struggle for the reformed church</i>, 78-82. The professor was following Grindal\'s trail, and revealed no further correspondence between the two men after Grindsl\'s 1558 letter to Foxe, from the ship that took him to a Bisghopric in London. Grindal wrote to Foxe stlil in Basle \'to hold up production\' of his [Foxe\'s] proposed Latin edition</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See Bennedict Robinson Collected <i>Letters of the Reformation\' and [John Strype],</i> Ecclesiastical History <i>vol I-III.</i></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">John Foxe, <i>Actes and Monuments</i> (London, Day, 1570) p&#160;715.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-ecclesiastical1983-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ecclesiastical1983_9-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ecclesiastical1983_9-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">John Milner, <i>History Civil and Ecclesiastical and Survey of Antiquities of Winchester</i> (1795), cited in Warren Wooden, <i>John Foxe</i> (Twayne, 1983), 106.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Linking Foxe\'s text to nationalism is so conventional that it had become \'old hat\', as Patrick Collinson observed, while composing another essay expressing the connection between Foxe\'s text and nationalism -- which is not the same as exhibiting a connection between religious sentiment and nationalism. The nineteenth-century Welsh chose to break away from the Anglican Church as a matter of politics and an expression of national ethnic and linguistic difference that they intended not to lose entirely.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Foxe and other <a href="/wiki/English_Reformation" title="English Reformation">English reformers</a> interpreted Wycliffe as a forerunner (indeed, "the morning star") of the Reformation.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Leslie M. Oliver, "The Seventh edition of <i>Actes and Monuments,"</i> <i>Papers of the American Bibliographic Society,</i> no 37 (1943), pp 243-60.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Helen White, <i>Tudor Books of Saints and Martyrs</i> (Madison UP, 1963); HalLer, <i>Elect Nation</i>, 227-8; 242-3[ 250-52.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">For the "never idled debate," see George Townsend, "Life and Defence of John Foxe," in <i>Acts and Monuments</i>, 8 vols. Josiah Pratt, ed. (New York: AMS, 1965, 5th ed.), pp I:2-151; Patrick Collinson, \xe2\x80\x9cTruth and Legend: the Veracity of John Foxe\'s <i>Book of Martyrs</i>" in <i>Clio\'s Mirror: Historiography in Britain and the Netherlands</i> A.C. Duke and C.A. Tamse, eds.(Zutphen, 1985) pp 31-54; Devorah Greenberg, \xe2\x80\x9cTruth and Veracity: The Legend of \'Foxe\',\xe2\x80\x9d presented at the 5th "John Foxe Congress": <i>John Foxe and the Catholic Tradition,</i> Magdalene College, Cambridge University, 5\xe2\x80\x937 July 2004.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFBirken" class="citation encyclopaedia">Birken, William. "Foxe, Simeon". <i><a href="/wiki/Dictionary_of_National_Biography#Oxford_Dictionary_of_National_Biography" title="Dictionary of National Biography">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</a></i> (online ed.). Oxford University Press. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1093%2Fref%3Aodnb%2F10053">10.1093/ref:odnb/10053</a>.</cite><span ti