ame of Alan Cope, <i>Dialogi sex, contra summi pontificatus, monasticae vitae, sanctorum, sacrarum imaginum oppugnatores, et pseudomartyres</i> (1566), a thousand page book, with the sixth dialogue aimed at Foxe. Mozley, 139.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Mozley, 138.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Freeman, ODNB. "In short, Foxe reacted to Harpsfield\'s challenge like the commander of a besieged city, abandoning what could not be defended and fortifying what could. Harpsfield drove Foxe to more intensive and extensive research and made his martyrology a more impressive, although not necessarily more accurate, work of scholarship."</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Mozley, p 141.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Mozley, p 147.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Mozley, 148-49.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">John N. King, <i>Foxe\'s Book of Martyrs: Select Narratives</i> (Oxford University Press, 2009), xli.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">David L. Jeffrey (January 1992). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zD6xVr1CizIC&amp;pg=PA697"><i>A Dictionary of Biblical Tradition in English Literature</i></a>. Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing. p.&#160;697. <a href="/wiki/International_S